properties.Name: DunBradstreetConsolidatedFinancialStatement
properties.Description: Consolidated financial statements are the Financial statements of a group in which the assets, liabilities, equity, income, expenses and cash flows of the company and its subsidiaries are presented as those of a single economic entity.

Columns.Name: DunsNumber
Columns.Description: Dun & Bradstreet (D&B) provides a D-U-N-S Number, a unique nine digit identification number, for each physical location of your business.

Columns.Name: ReportPurchaseDate
Columns.Description: The purchase date of the report.

Columns.Name: ReferenceCurrencyName
Columns.Description: The reference currency name.

Columns.Name: CashAmount
Columns.Description: Net cash is a company's total cash minus total liabilities when discussing financial statements. Net cash is commonly used in evaluating a company's cash flow, and can refer to the amount of cash remaining after a transaction has been completed once all charges and deductions related to the transaction have been subtracted.

Columns.Name: AccountsReceivableAmount
Columns.Description: Accounts receivable refers to the outstanding invoices a company has or the money the company is owed from its clients.

Columns.Name: InventoryAmount
Columns.Description: Business inventories are essentially the amount of all products available to sell to other businesses and/or the end consumer.

Columns.Name: OtherCurrentAssetsAmount
Columns.Description: A firm's assets that do not include cash, securities, receivables, inventory and prepaid assets, and can be convertible into cash within one business cycle, which is usually one year.

Columns.Name: TotalCurrentAssetsAmount
Columns.Description:
"Total current assets" is the sum of cash, accounts receivable, inventory and supplies. 

Other assets that appear in the balance sheet are called long-term or fixed assets because they're durable and will last more than one year.

Columns.Name: FixturesAndEquipmentAmount
Columns.Description: Furniture, fixtures and equipment, abbreviated FF&E or FFE, are movable furniture, fixtures or other equipment that have no permanent connection to the structure of a building or utilities. These items depreciate substantially over their long-term use, but they are definitely important costs to consider when valuing a company, especially during liquidation procedures.

Columns.Name: OtherAssetsAmount
Columns.Description: A firm's assets that do not include cash, securities, receivables, inventory and prepaid assets, and can be convertible into cash within one business cycle, which is usually one year.

Columns.Name: TotalAssetsAmount
Columns.Description:
The basic accounting equation states that assets = liabilities + stockholders' equity. In the accounting industry, assets are defined as anything that a business owns, has value, and can be converted to cash.

Assets are broken down into two main categories. These two categories are current assets and noncurrent assets.

Columns.Name: AccountsPayableAmount
Columns.Description: Accounts payable (AP) is an accounting entry that represents an entity's obligation to pay off a short-term debt to its creditors.

Columns.Name: NotesPayableAmount
Columns.Description: Notes Payable is a general ledger account in which a company records the face amounts of the promissory notes that it has issued. The amounts for the promissory notes (or simply notes) that have not been repaid are reported as part of the company's liabilities.

Columns.Name: LongTermLiabilitiesAmount
Columns.Description: Long-term liabilities are liabilities with a future benefit over one year, such as notes payable that mature longer than one year.

Columns.Name: OtherCurrentLiabilitiesAmount
Columns.Description: Other current liabilities are a company's debts or obligations that are due within one year, appearing on the company's balance sheet and include short term debt, accounts payable, accrued liabilities and other debts.

Columns.Name: TotalCurrentLiabilitiesAmount
Columns.Description: Current liabilities are a company's debts or obligations that are due within one year, appearing on the company's balance sheet and include short term debt, accounts payable, accrued liabilities and other debts.

Columns.Name: CommonStockAmount
Columns.Description: The amount of common stock outstanding.

Columns.Name: RetainedEarningsAmount
Columns.Description: Retained earnings refer to the percentage of net earnings not paid out as dividends, but retained by the company to be reinvested in its core business, or to pay debt. It is recorded under shareholders' equity on the balance sheet.

Columns.Name: TotalLiabilitiesAmount
Columns.Description: Total liabilities are the aggregate debt and financial obligations owed by a business to individuals and organizations at any specific period of time.

Columns.Name: TotalNetWorthAmount
Columns.Description: Net worth (sometimes called net or wealth) is the total assets minus total outside liabilities of an individual or a company.

Properties.Description: Consolidated financial statements are the Financial statements of a group in which the assets, liabilities, equity, income, expenses and cash flows of the company and its subsidiaries are presented as those of a single economic entity.
